name: Mount Flume

trails_config.name: Lincoln Woods & Osseo Trail
trails_config.description: A longer but gentle approach from the east: hike the flat Lincoln Woods Trail along the river, then ascend via the Osseo Trail’s switchbacks and ladders through serene birch forest. This route pops out just below Flume’s summit, avoiding the more dangerous slide. The summit itself is a small rocky knob with tremendous views into Franconia Notch and toward Mount Liberty.

trails_config.name: Flume Slide Trail
trails_config.description: A challenging classic loop: ascend the Flume Slide Trail, which climbs relentlessly up a wet, steep rock slab requiring hands-and-feet scrambling (not recommended in wet conditions). After conquering the slide to reach the summit of Flume, traverse to Mount Liberty and descend Liberty Spring Trail for a less hazardous return. This expert route is a thrill for seasoned hikers seeking a heart-pounding ascent and big views.

current_conditions.ai_summary: Experience the beauty of New Hampshire on Mount Flume. At 4328 feet, this summit commands impressive views of the surrounding wilderness.
risk_factors: Check local trail conditions before departing.
Start early to avoid afternoon storms.

generated_description:
The Experience

Standing at 4328 feet, Mount Flume is a standout peak in New Hampshire. Known for its approachable and scenic terrain, it offers a quintessential hiking experience.

The Challenge

Hikers often choose the **Lincoln Woods & Osseo Trail**, a **11.2 mile** route gaining significant elevation. As part of the **NH48 4000-Footers**, it draws peak-baggers from across the region.

Peak Bagging Logic

**Peak Bagging Opportunity:** Consider connecting this hike with **Mount Liberty**, which is just 1.3 miles away. Linking these peaks is a popular way to maximize your day on the trail.
